In JavaScript, you can use URL-safe base64 encoding and decoding for your purpose. Base64 is a group of binary-to-text encoding schemes that are used commonly on the Internet.

Here's a simple example of encoding and decoding a string using the built-in `btoa` (base64 encoding) and `atob` (base64 decoding) functions in JavaScript:

```javascript
// Encoding
const longString = "your long string up to 100 characters";
const encodedString = btoa(longString);
console.log(encodedString);

// Decoding
const decodedString = atob(encodedString);
console.log(decodedString);
```

Keep in mind that base64 encoding will increase the length of your string by approximately 33%, so it's not ideal for extremely long strings. If you have a very long string, consider using other compression algorithms like gzip or LZString library.

To use base64 encoding in a URL, you can first encode your string, then encode the encoded string using `encodeURIComponent` function to ensure that special characters are properly encoded:

```javascript
const encodedUriComponentString = encodeURIComponent(btoa(longString));
const encodedUrl = `https://yourwebsite.com/decode?encodedString=${encodedUriComponentString}`;
console.log(encodedUrl);
```

On the receiving end, you can decode the base64 encoded string and then decode the URI component:

```javascript
const decodedLongString = atob(decodeURIComponent('your encodedUriComponentString'));
```

This way, you can share your long string via a URL, and the recipient can easily decode it on the other end.

